ce in the story of women’s suffrage. Understanding the need for popular approval for any social change, these socialites used their wealth, power, social connections and style to excite mainstream interest and to diffuse resistance to the cause. In the end, as Neuman says, when change was in the air, these women helped push women’s suffrage over the finish line.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aElite (Social sciences)zNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocialiteszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aSuffragistszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aSuffragistszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSuffragezNew York (State)xHistory. 0aWomenxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen--Suffrage--New York (State)--History. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479877515.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479877515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479877515/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles